body:
I have a number of test classes that share a database very poorly, via a shared `IDisposable` base class; if the tests run in parallel, they fail because the shared state can't be shared.

Adding `[assembly: CollectionBehavior(CollectionBehavior.CollectionPerAssembly)]` to the assembly's AssemblyInfo makes the tests run sequentially (they're all in the same assembly) and all pass.

However, if I instead use `[assembly: CollectionBehavior(DisableTestParallelization = true)]` it does not work; the tests still run in parallel to some extent and fail.

I can replicate this with a very simple analogue. For the shared state, something along the lines of

```
public class SharedState : IDisposable
{
    private static readonly object sync = new object();
    protected static int Instances;

    public SharedState()
    {
        lock (sync)
        {
            Instances++;
            File.AppendAllLines("testlog.txt", new [] { string.Format("{0,2} {1,3} {2}", Instances, "in", this.GetType())});
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        lock (sync)
        {
            Instances--;
            File.AppendAllLines("testlog.txt", new[] { string.Format("{0,2} {1,3} {2}", Instances, "out", this.GetType()) });
        }
    }
}
```

and then for the tests, ten test classes with ten test methods each along these lines:

```
public class Class1 : SharedState
{
    [Fact]
    public void Test1()
    {
        Assert.Equal(1, Instances);
    }
    ... 9 more of these
}
```

This results in many test failures, and a log file like

```
1  in MyTestLibrary.Class1
2  in MyTestLibrary.Class10
1 out MyTestLibrary.Class10
2  in MyTestLibrary.Class10
1 out MyTestLibrary.Class1
0 out MyTestLibrary.Class10
```

showing that the tests are executing in parallel.

If I additionally log the `ManagedThreadId` of the thread used on each test, I get two distinct thread IDs on my two-core system.

Have I misunderstood this attribute or is it not working?
